This is Robert. His momma was a stray who showed up one day and left him and some siblings in my care. I didn’t want a cat, and I gave them all normal people names. I found homes for John, Susan, Douglas, and Mildred, but I found myself not wanting to part ways with Robert. He was too friendly, too playful, and too social. If a visitor comes, he will visit with them. I was always under the impression that cats weren’t friendly and weren’t great pets, but Robert von Kittenheimer here, he’s shown me that they can be awesome members of my family. (I have three kids and he’s the first one I greet when I get home)
Silky looks brownish in the sunlight.
She will mess a feather up, tho.

images.description: I decided to go a different route home yesterday so I could stop at the store for some ice cream. Its head was smashed, but it didn't die right away. As I was about to turn around another kitchen showed up in the middle of the road. So I stopped traffic and scooped  it up. Unfortunately the orange kitten didn't make it.

This kitty found her way to our driveway almost a week ago. 
I was pulling up to my house after a few days away when I spotted her, with her kittens in tow. It was dark, but it was easy to see how skinny they all were. We own two cats already so we had extra food, bedding, and toys for them.
   We don't know where they came from or how they got all the way to us, because we live on a very rural part of a state highway. She certainly has been through a lot and is a clever momma to get here relatively unscathed.

A friend recommended a local cat rescue that helps control the stray cat population by spaying/neutering, vaccinating, and microchipping feral/abandoned cats. They are all volunteers and are funded by donations only. Unfortunately, summer is such a busy time of year for them that they have to prioritize kittens, so sadly adult cats often get overlooked for adoption.

Mars is one of the sweetest cats I have ever met. Look at that face! She was definitely in the care of people at some point because she loves to be picked up and cuddled. This poor girl is an indoor cat at heart and probably had a helluva time surviving, especially with a litter of kittens. After a few days of consistent food she started to lactate again and had had more energy, her personality really started to shine too.
   We love Mars an awful lot, but she seems unsure about other cats. We think it would be unfair for us to keep her, considering we already have two. If you or somebody you know can take her and give her a good home, please pm me for more information!

tl;dr Lovely kitty needs help finding a home. 

Edit: We live near Portland, OR

images.description: This is Maeby, she belongs to a dear friend of mine. Maeby was a neighborhood feral cat who recently adopted my friend and her family.

Last winter my friend decided to try and catch this cat after she noticed that one of her eyes was badly infected. Through advice and help from the local rescue shelter, my friend was able to win over the cat's trust.
After a little while, Maeby happily entered my friend's home. You can see the love in her face.
